siness, academia, and religion. Human beings' internalization of agonistic drives, he concludes, can foster the deeper discovery of the self and of distinctively human freedom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCompetition (Psychology). 0aConsciousness. 0aHuman beings. 0aLife. 0aSex differences (Psychology). 0aSociobiology. 4aGender Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPsychology & Psychiatry. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Men's Studies.2bisacsh  amacho image, machismo, sports fans, sports and gender, don quixote, male agonistic drive, gender evolution.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146629840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801466298423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801466298/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles